sec.p:
Thermoelectric (TE) generators are considered as an eco-friendly solution to the global warming issue, since they can convert waste heat into electricity1–5. They have received considerable attention owing to their scalability, cleanliness, and long operating life6–8. A good TE material can improve the efficiency of photovoltaic9–11 and thermophotonic12 devices. The conversion efficiency of a TE material is measured by a dimensionless parameter called figure of merit (ZT)13–15 as below:1ZT=S2σTκe+κL=PFκe+κLT,\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\begin{aligned} ZT=\frac{S^2\sigma T}{~\kappa _e+\kappa _L~}=\frac{PF}{~\kappa _e+\kappa _L~}T, \end{aligned}$$\end{document}where S, σ\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\sigma$$\end{document}, and T are the Seebeck coefficient, electrical conductivity, and absolute temperature, while κe\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa _e$$\end{document} and κL\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$\kappa _L$$\end{document} stand for the electronic and lattice thermal conductivities, respectively. Generally, a promising TE material must have a large power factor (PF=S2σ)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(PF=S^2\sigma )$$\end{document} and low thermal conductivity (κ=κe+κL)\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$(\kappa =\kappa _e+\kappa _L)$$\end{document}. However, due to the complex correlations among the quantities, it is very difficult to achieve a large ZT.

